Starting a new theory course. All information is strictly confidential.
Hey, Ferb, should we start building the world's coolest rollercoaster?
You know me, I'm a man of action. But we need a scientific approach.
Of course, a scientific approach is our speciality!
We have to use parts of different sizes, so that the track will turn out really cool.
Definitely! Our coaster will be the tallest, longest, and coolest in the world! Hey, what do you mean by "size"?
Look! That top box is twice as lnog as Perry! Great measurement tool!
An object may be shorter or longer than others.
Great! If I stood on your shoulders, we would be twice as high!
An object may be lower, higher, or the same height as another.
I know width is also called thickness. For example, a thick book.
An object may be narrower or wider or the same width as another object.
The length, width, and height define the dimensions of an object.
All cars of the same model have the same dimensions and are therefore the same size.
An object may be larger, smaller, or the same size as another.
And the platypus is the only way to measure the dimensions of objects?
Of course not! Length, width, and height can be measured with a ruler, which is divided up into pieces called centimeters.
You can put the ruler next to the subject and see how many centimeters fit in it.
Ferb, you messed up the drawing again! The trash is already full!
This is because it has a small volume...
Mom said that I'm in charge! And I have my eyes on you...
The volume of one object may be smaller, larger, or the same as another.
Volume is the space occupied by an object. The longer, taller, and wider the object is, the greater its volume, and the more space it takes up.
To measure the volume of these two boxes, we can put same-sized cubes in them.
The first box fit eight blocks, and the second only fit six.
That means the volume of the first box is greater than that of the second!
And what if we don't have those cubes?
Volume can be measured with water. Pour water into the tank and the bucket. The bucket fits less water than the tank, so its volume is less.
I hope that all made sense, now you can help us build a rollercoaster!
But just in case, let's do a quick test!
Mom! Phineas and Ferb built a rollercoaster! Look!
Wow! Phineas and Ferb built a rollercoaster!
Let's take the flyer! Maybe we'll get a discount!
I don't understand! There was a poster just a moment ago!
Stop dreaming and help me with the cart... you have no idea how much it weighs!
Candace! You learned about it in school two years ago, you should know!
I guess I forgot. Can you remind me?
Right! A small apple is heavier than a large balloon!
An object may be heavier or lighter than another.
You can compare the weight of two objects by holding them in your hands.
Yeah! This watermelon is much heavier than an apple.
The heavier object will move your hand down harder.
We determine the weight of an object with a scale.
The needle shows how heavy the object is!
Heavier objects will press harder on the scale.
The scale measures the weight of the object in a sepcific unit, kilograms.
I got it! This watermelon weighs 8 kg.
The dial is divided into equal segments, and if you put an object that weighs one kilogram on the scale, the needle will move exactly one segment.
Objects of equal weight balance each other.
Apparently one liter of water weighs one kilogram.
Exactly. They press on the scales the same amount, so they balance each other out.
Combining items also adds their weight.
Therefore, if the shopping cart has too many items, it will be hard to push it!
Some objects are so hot that you can't touch them with your bare hands or you'll get burned.
An object may be warmer or colder or have the same temperature as others.
The temperature of an object may change if it is hot or cold.
Yes, yes! If you put ice cream in a bag with hot donuts, it will heat up and melt!
And if you put a hot donuts into a box of ice, it will quickly freeze.
We can measure temperature using a thermometer.
When the temperature of the object increases, that means that it's warmer. When it falls, it's colder.
If the bars in the thermometer go up, it means that the temperature is increasing. If they do down, it's decreasing
The temperature is measured in degrees. It may be below or above zero.
Degrees? That sounds familiar... oh yeah! Ninety degrees is a right angle!
The thermometer scale is divided into equal segments, each of which is equal to one degree.
Zero degrees is in the middle. And that means...
The freezing point of water is used as a point of reference when measureing temperature. It's a convient solution because water is everywhere on Earth. It's in people, plants, and animals.
But I saw the poster with my own eyes!
You should calm down a little... come on, let's go shopping, it's relaxing!
Alright! Everything is ready! Time to start the coolest ride ever!
Wait! First you have to count all the passengers and cars. Otherwise it won't work!
These calculations must be very accurate! The safety of the riders depends of them!
First you need to repeat the theory. Just in case.
Addition is a mathematical operation that combines two or more numbers into one.
This operation is marked with a plus sign (+), which is placed between the two numbers being added.
The sum is written after the equal sign (=).
The numbers that we add are called addends and the number that we get as the result is called the sum.
Addition is like putting things in a basket.
Yes! If you put three apples and three pears in a basket, there will be six fruit.
If you add zero to any number, the sum is the same, that is, the number does not change.
Of course, zero is nothing after all...
There's one more rule in addition: changing the order of the summands doesn't change the sum.
I understand! When adding numbers, it doesn't matter which we add first.
This is the opposite of adding! Instead of counting, we subtract.
Subtraction is taking away from one number another number which is the same size or smaller.
The number we subtract from is the minuend, the number we subtract is the subtrahend, and the result is the difference.
Are you trying to mess with my head?
No, it's easy! Minuend is the nubmer which becomes smaller. Subtrahend is the part that's removed from the minuend. And the difference is what's left!
And what if we subtract three apples from three cars?
Nothing. We can only subtract the same kinds of things from each other.
If you subtract a number from itself, you get zero.
Yeah... if I have three apples and eat them all, then I'll have nothing left.
And if we subtract zero from any number, it stays the same.
You can subtract zero? Sero is nothing, after all.
Exactly! If you subtract zero, nothing will change!
Alright, now everything is ready for a crazy adventure!
